shortContent.en-US: It is our goal to encourage the next generation of leaders to build great companies of enduring meaning and value, so we launched our Atomic Fellowship Program for graduate and undergraduate students.

fullContent.en-US:
It is our goal to encourage the next generation of leaders to build great companies of enduring meaning and value, so we launched our Atomic Fellowship Program for graduate and undergraduate students.
Our Fellowship has three main pillars:

1. Value Creation: Fellows are empowered to immediately contribute and create value on 0-to-1 initiatives.

2. Community: Company building is a team sport, we host events and activities to foster community in the cohort. Fellows will invariably be the leaders of tomorrow.

3. Diversity of Thought: Diversity of backgrounds and skills creates better opportunities to learn and expand thinking.

2020 was our Fellowships inaugural year. We had 567 applicants in two weeks. With only ten spots available, candidate selection became a challenging task. Our acceptance rate was on course to be lower than even the most prestigious colleges (1.76%). Ultimately we made some tough decisions and chose an absolutely amazing cohort.

When COVID hit and San Francisco went into lockdown, companies began canceling summer programs left and right. Not us. We believe it has never been a better time to start a company. Our incredible team quickly pivoted from the original plan and enabled us to host a fully-remote Fellowship Program. But this change raised some important questions:

  Can a remote Fellowship offer a comparable amount of value to an in-person Fellowship?
 Will the Fellows feel connected to Atomic and to each other?
  Would the cohort be able to learn and deliver on projects effectively?

After 12 weeks, we can report the answer was a resounding YES to each of those questions. Every week was full of CEO fireside chats from around Atomic, courses from external experts, peer to peer lessons, socials, and self-organized jam sessions to work through intractable problems.

Each Fellow provided demonstrable value in ways that exceeded expectations. From tackling huge problems, building custom web applications, re-designing parts of the conversion funnel, intensely researching and pitching companies, building out painted door tests and MVPs, to synthesizing huge data sets  Fellows quickly became important members of the Atomic Family.

We plan to continue the program next summer and cannot wait to see what the next round of Fellows bring to the table. We will begin hiring for the summer cohort starting in February. Although we are not actively looking for Fellows during the rest of the year, we do encourage anyone who thinks theyve got what it takes to create value at Atomic to submit an application.

title.en-US: Replicant The Future of Customer Service

shortContent.en-US: When we started Replicant in 2017, we certainly did not predict that a global pandemic would create a customer service disaster, suddenly accelerating businesses into AI and automation.

fullContent.en-US:
When we started Replicant in 2017, we certainly did not predict that a global pandemic would create a customer service disaster, suddenly accelerating businesses into AI and automation. We merely believed that machines were ready to have useful, complex conversations with people and that the future business applications of this could be profound.

We look around us today (while living in a dystopian scene from our namesake film) and know the world has turned upside down over the past six months. For businesses  call centers have shut down due to Covid-19, customer service call volumes have surged unpredictability, and customers are more frustrated than ever with long wait times leading to unresolved issues. Replicants autonomous call center is now enabling these businesses to fully resolve customer issues (even the most complex ones) over the phone with natural-sounding conversations  improving the customer experience while reducing costs.


Hundreds of millions of consumers use voice assistants such as Amazon Alexa or Apples Siri for simple tasks in their daily lives. Now, one company wants to take talking bots to the next level: the highly conversational field of customer service.

Replicant, named after Blade Runners genetically engineering humans, is entering uncharted territory with its software...
Forbes


Startups have moments. Replicants is now. The company is now handling over two million autonomous customer support calls a month, grown over 15X in revenue in just six months, and is partnering with some of the largest enterprises and call centers in the world. Were inspired by how this incredible team, led by our co-founders Gadi Shamia (CEO) and Benjamin Gleitzman (CTO), have fearlessly seized their moment during this pandemic to help businesses and customers across the globe.

Were excited to share today that with Replicant, Atomic has made one of our most significant investments in any company to-date, and partnered with Scott Beechuk at Norwest Venture Partners who led a $27 million investment in the company, alongside a group of co-investors deeply experienced with the intersection of AI and the enterprise: Mark Selcow at Costanoa Ventures, James Cham at Bloomberg Beta, and State Farm Ventures. Scott, who is intimately familiar with the customer service software industry from his time as SVP Product for Salesforce Service Cloud points out why Replicant is well positioned:


(Replicants) attention to this humanscale connection is what sets them apart in the customer service arena: they start with the experience between caller and agent and build their AI-driven product around it. The result is a first-of-its-kind product that honors the human aspect of customer service no matter how automated operations get.


The company has come a long way from its humble beginnings converting our storage closet into a closely guarded private office where Benjamin Gleitzmans hand-picked team of AI and machine learning engineers started building the worlds first autonomous call center. But we know this is just the beginning and couldnt be more hopeful about the future of customer service.

title.en-US: Global leader in face recognition technology.

desc.en-US: We created Paravision to provide highly accurate face recognition technology to enterprise partners aiming to build a more secure, frictionless world. Paravision has optimized its models (delivered as SDKs and APIs) for a range of deployments (from cloud to edge) and use cases (surveillance, access control, payments). Paravision is the only US-based company to rank in the top 10 in 50 accuracy benchmarks across NISTs 1:1 and 1:N face recognition tests.

We created Raydiant because nearly 50% of screens sold every year dont end up in living rooms  they are in businesses. Everywhere you go you see screens and screens: restaurants, bars, offices, stores, hotels, gyms, doctor offices, museums, stadiums. Raydiant enables cloud-based, multi-screen programming and management for businesses. Like Meraki (Cisco) did for networking hardware, Raydiant is doing so for screens.

We created Remrise because the way we sleep, rest, and recover is just as purposeful and consequential as the way we spend our days. Remrise combines the best of the East and the West offering rotational, personalized, plant-based formulas, combined with a dynamic suite of tools, including sleep tracking and meditation, to improve sleep over time.

We created Replicant because machines are ready to have useful, complex conversations that will transform the way they interact with the world. Customer service often doesn't serve the customer or the business. Replicant is a conversational AI platform that instantly solves problems over the phone, improves customer experience, and reduces cost.

title.en-US: Voice AI to understand and optimize conversations

desc.en-US: We created TalkIQ because nearly 70% of customer interactions are still over the phone, yet this data  the insights from the most critical customer conversations  is not being captured, analyzed, or leveraged to grow and improve a business. TalkIQ is used by sales teams and customer support centers to increase revenue, improve customer engagement, and ultimately build better products.

We created Terminal because the future of work is global, and the biggest problem facing companies is scaling technical talent. Terminal provides a turnkey solution for building and scaling remote engineering in global campuses across Canada and Mexico. The fastest growing teams like Atrium, Dialpad, Earnin, Eventbrite, KeepTruckin, Gusto are accelerated by Terminal.

We created Zenreach to solve one of the most important problems for brick and mortar businesses  the majority of our time is spent online, yet the majority of purchasing still happens offline  and there is no link between the two. Zenreach is a platform that connects online marketing with in-store results to drive 4X better digital marketing performance for customers like BCBG, IHOP, Johnny Rockets, and Peet's Coffee.

Always thinking that everything is awesome (!!!)

title.en-US: What did you want to be when you grew up?

text.en-US: Someone who does cool stuff at cool companies. I've long tried to figure out what that meant, job-wise, and made a big step towards that ideal while at Qatalyst -- being a trusted advisor to many amazing companies helped me realize that there's a huge benefit to working across companies, bringing broadly-sourced insights and learnings on how to be better, grow faster, and get to a better exit (whatever that exit may be!). At Qatalyst, we were known for helping companies achieve outsized values through M&A; I'm betting that by getting involved earlier and helping *build* the companies, we'll get to a new level of outsized outcomes.

title.en-US: What sparked your interest in the world of entrepreneurship?

text.en-US: Shad Valley, a summer program for high school students that emphasized entrepreneurship and ended with a business plan competition. Back in 2005, our team came up with an idea for a PDA-like device integrated with a prickless near-infrared sensor for measuring and managing blood glucose, without needing to manually track and calculate dosages. Which was a super cool idea (and one that others have mostly implemented since then)! Some VCs even reached out to us. But there was so much more we needed to learn; we completely lacked the technical or business know-how to make it happen. This led me to pursue a business education in parallel with engineering, so I'd be able to help make something like this a reality.

title.en-US: Why do you believe in Atomic?

text.en-US: I've seen the power of the Atomic model in practice, accelerating and empowering our companies. It's truly an unfair advantage, with the focus and hustle of bootstrapping joined with the resources and experience of an institutional investor, advisor, and operating team that stays invested and committed over the long term. I love watching our companies race out of the gates, take the lead, and stay there.
Trying to beat my previous time. Wanting to do better and be better at all I try to do.
